## Q1 — The Nabataean Agriculture: what genuinely survives

The *al-Filāḥa al-Nabaṭiyya* (الفلاحة النبطية) presented by Ibn Waḥshiyya c. 904 CE is, on the current scholarly consensus (Jaakko Hämeen-Anttila, *The Last Pagans of Iraq*, Brill 2006), **a composite late-antique Iraqi work whose Syriac substrate dates to roughly the 6th century CE**, not an authentic ancient Babylonian corpus. It genuinely preserves real late-pagan praxis but not pre-Mosaic Babylonian revelation. The 19th-century debate ran from Daniel Chwolsohn (1856, claiming a 16th-c. BCE original) through Alfred von Gutschmid (1861) and Theodor Nöldeke (1875, dismissing the whole as forgery) to Toufic Fahd (critical edition 1993–98, more credulous than Hämeen-Anttila) to the current Brill consensus.

**(a) Tammūz lamentations** [VH]. NA pp. 296–299 (= Hämeen-Anttila Text 24), preserved verbatim in Maimonides *Guide* III:29: Tammūzā is a prophet who calls his king to worship the seven planets and twelve zodiacal signs; the king kills him repeatedly; on the night of his final death "all the idols from the eastern and western parts of the world gathered in the temple of the Sun in Bābil, around the great golden idol that is suspended between heaven and earth … and the idol of the Sun stood in the middle of the temple and began to mourn for Tammūzā … hence the women weep, wail, mourn and lament for Tammūz on the first day of the month of Tammūz." Ibn Waḥshiyya's own translator's gloss at NA p. 298 — "even though the Sabians know the name and story of Tammūz(ā), they are ignorant of the name of Yanbūshād" — is itself diagnostic of stratified, living tradition. Independent corroboration in Ibn al-Nadīm, *Fihrist* p. 318, on the festival of *al-Būqāt* in Tammūz among the Ḥarrān Syrians. This is the single strongest survival of a real Mesopotamian cult into the early Islamic Iraqi countryside.

**(b) Astral rituals** [VH for the texts; H for the Aramaic substrate]. NA pp. 10–12 (= LP Text 7) opens with an invocation of **Zuḥal/Saturn** (= Aramaic *Kēwān*), with chthonic attributes — black animals, stones, plants — and a holocaust of fourteen black bats and fourteen black rats. The preserved prayer contains a corrupt Aramaic transliteration (*KYW'N'*, *M'RY DSHMY' M'RY 'R'W*) glossed in Arabic as *rabb al-samāʾ wa-rabb al-arḍ* — Lord of heaven and Lord of earth. The seven-planet hierarchy is fully articulated (al-Shams supreme; al-Qamar; al-Mushtarī = Greater Benefic; al-Zuhara = Lesser Benefic; al-Mirrīkh = Greater Malefic; Zuḥal = Lesser Malefic but patron of agriculture; ʿUṭārid). al-Shiʿrā (Sirius) and the pre-Islamic Arabian *Nasr* are also named. The Sun is "the soul (*nafs*) of the upper and lower worlds." Maimonides, paraphrasing NA, records: "golden images to the sun, images of silver to the moon," and the seven-beetles-seven-mice-seven-bats offering.

**(c) Agricultural magic and talismans** [VH]. Maimonides, *Guide* III:37, quotes NA verbatim on a rotting-substance talisman scattered round fruit trees and "more efficient than any kind of witchcraft in accelerating productiveness" — the very passage Maimonides uses to explain the Torah's *ʿorlah* prohibition as anti-Sabian polemic. The "althea-of-Nineveh" said to have stood 12,000 years, the speaking mandrake (NA p. 1416), the invisibility-leaf, and a proto-Golem recipe for artificial-man generation by manipulating heat, blood, semen and astral hours (NA pp. 1318–1319) constitute the largest single late-antique Near Eastern plant-magic dossier extant.

**(d) Named deities and sages** [VH for names, M for historicity]. Beyond the planets and Tammūzā, NA names a chain of pre-biblical sages — **Dawānāy** (the "Lord of Mankind," likely from Aramaic *ʾDWN'* = Adon), **Adamā** (Adam astralized as lunar prophet, forefather *only* of the Kasdānians, not of universal humanity), **Ishītā** (Seth, who differs from Adam in worshipping the moon — Maimonides III:29), **Anūḥā** (a Noah/Enoch contamination, treated as wisdom-prophet not flood-survivor), **Ṣaghrīth, Yanbūshād, Quthāmā** (the foundational, expanding, and completing redactors of the agricultural treatise). Crucially, NA p. 1264 states that the Jarāmiqa "are not from the progeny of Adam" — a **pre-Adamic / co-Adamic** doctrine 700 years before Isaac La Peyrère.

**(e) Creation/flood narratives** [H; NULL on a positive Genesis-rival cosmogony]. The Sabian cosmology is **eternalist** — Maimonides III:29 confirms: "All the Sabeans thus believed in the eternity of the Universe." There is no creation *ex nihilo*, no Atrahasis, no Enuma Elish in NA. There is no global-flood narrative in the biblical sense; Anūḥā is a sage, not Noah. **NULL**: NA does not preserve a coherent alternative cosmogonic narrative. The "20,000-year antiquity" claim in the preface is *explicitly undercut* by the text's own admission of *ramz* (symbolic numerology) usage (LP p. 30).

**Assessment of project framework.** The narrow "NA preserves authentic late-antique Iraqi pagan religion that the Abrahamic traditions later treated as idolatry" is **well-grounded** [H–VH]. The strong "NA is a 20,000-year-old Babylonian revelation preserved despite Mosaic suppression" is **the very claim Ibn Waḥshiyya made and his own text undermines** [L]. NA was not even "suppressed" — Maimonides, Ibn Khaldūn, the *Picatrix*, and Ibn al-ʿAwwām all cite it openly.

