## Q2 — Qos / Qaus: an Edomite YHWH-parallel hiding in plain sight

The mainstream picture: **Qos (קוס / Qauš)** is the national god of Edom, etymologically a bow/storm/warrior deity (Arabic *qaws* = bow; cognate to the rainbow-archer *Quzaḥ*; cf. Ernst A. Knauf, DDD² 674–677), functionally parallel to YHWH, attested from the late 8th century BCE into the Nabataean–Roman period.

**(a) Idumaean ostraca** [H; M on specific numbering]. The 4th-c. BCE Aramaic ostraca from the Maresha/Khirbet el-Kôm region, published by Eph'al & Naveh (1996), Lemaire (1996, 2002), and Porten & Yardeni (TAO, 2014–20), preserve **69 distinct Qos-theophoric names** (Bezalel Porten, "A Name is a Prayer," De Gruyter 2021, 286–290). Qos-bearing individuals constitute ~27–28% of the named population (Tebes 2023). A Horvat ʿUza ostracon (Beit-Arieh 2007) preserves the formula *w-hbrktk l-qws* "I bless you by Qos" — structurally identical to YHWHistic blessings at Kuntillet ʿAjrud and Arad. Two inscriptions from the open-air Edomite shrine at Horvat Qitmit (7th c. BCE) read simply לקוס "to/by Qos."

**(b) Theophoric names — Akkadian primary citation** [VH]. **RINAP 4, Esarhaddon 1, col. v, lines 54–60** (Leichty 2011, p. 23):

> *(55) Ba-ʾa-lu LUGAL URU Ṣur-ri Me-na-si-i LUGAL URU Ia-ú-di / (56) **Qa-uš-gab-ri LUGAL KUR Ú-du-mu** Mu-ṣu-ri LUGAL KUR Ma-ʾa-ba…*

"I summoned the kings of Ḫatti and Eber-nāri: Baʿalu king of Tyre, **Manasseh king of Judah, Qauš-gabri king of Edom**, Muṣuru king of Moab…" The cuneiform 𒋡𒍑𒃮𒊑 *Qa-uš-gab-ri* means "Qauš is a warrior/is mighty." The same king bears a bulla from Umm el-Biyara: **לקוסגבר מלך אדם** "(belonging) to Qos-gabar, king of Edom." His predecessor **Qauš-malaka** ("Qauš has become king") appears in **RINAP 1 (Tadmor & Yamada), Tiglath-Pileser III text 47, line 11**, as western tributary alongside Ahaz of Judah (~734 BCE). The Hebrew name **קושיהו Qushayāhū** in 1 Chr 15:17 may be a syncretistic Qos+YHWH compound (so Vriezen 1965, Bartlett 1989, Rainey 1997) — **contested by Knauf [M]**. Costobarus (Κοστόβαρος = *Qos-gabar*), Herod's governor of Idumaea, was said by Josephus (*Ant.* 15.7.9 §253–266) to be from "the chief house of the Idumaeans, whose ancestors had been priests of Qoze (Κωζαι)" — the last historically dated Qos cultic figure.

**(c) Obed-Edom as Qos-worshipper** [H mainstream; L for the strong claim]. **2 Samuel 6:10–12** (Aleppo Codex) — וַיַּטֵּהוּ דָוִד בֵּית **עֹבֵד אֱדֹם הַגִּתִּי** … וַיְבָרֶךְ יְהוָה אֶת־עֹבֵד אֱדֹם — the Ark is diverted to "Obed-Edom the Gittite" for three months and YHWH blesses his house. **Chronicles systematically Levitizes him**: 1 Chr 15:18–25 makes him a Levitical musician; 1 Chr 16:38 anchors him in the Merarite Jeduthun line; 1 Chr 26:4–8 gives him 8 sons and 62 men "able for service" — *because God blessed him*, deliberately echoing 2 Sam 6:11. The mainstream onomastic reading (Thompson, ABD V:5–6; Knauf DDD² 274; Bartlett 1989:200; Tebes 2011, 2022; Rainey 1997; Amzallag 2015) is that **עבד אדום means "servant of (the god of) Edom" = Qos-worshipper, retroactively Levitized to legitimize the actual Persian-period presence of Edomite cultic personnel in the Second Temple** [H]. The Truth Project's specific extension ("he was a Qos priest later suppressed") goes beyond textual evidence [L] — there is no inscription naming a *kōhēn* of Qos and no extra-biblical Obed-Edom attestation.

**(d) Qos as storm/weather god — and continuity** [H storm; VH Nabataean]. Knauf (DDD² 676): "[Qos and YHWH] are forms of the Syrian–Arabian weather-god, among whose attributes the bow is as much a part as the storm." Qos's bow is functionally the rainbow of Gen 9:13 (*qaštî* "my bow" in the cloud) and the lightning-bow of Hab 3:9–11. The **Khirbet et-Tannur** Nabataean temple (McKenzie et al., ASOR 2013) preserves a Hellenistic enthroned bearded storm-god holding a multi-pronged thunderbolt, flanked by bull-calves — Hadad/Zeus iconography. The related sanctuary at **Khirbet edh-Dharih** names him in Nabataean Aramaic as קוס די בחורוא "Qos of Ḥurāwā." Healey (*The Religion of the Nabataeans*, Brill 2001, p. 140) treats Tannur as dedicated to "Qos-Dushara as a supreme deity." Greek transliterations Κωζαι/Κοζε attest cult continuity into the Roman period.

The southern-epiphany texts (Deut 33:2; Judg 5:4; Hab 3:3; Ps 68:8) place YHWH's origin in **Edom/Seir/Teman/Paran** — Qos's territory. The minority view (Rose 1977; Amzallag 2009) that Qos = YHWH outright is rejected by Bartlett, Knauf, Danielson, Tebes; the consensus is **two related but distinct deities** of the same Shasu-bedouin religious matrix [M for common origin].

