## Q3 — The Rephaim Banquet (KTU 1.20–1.22): dead, divine, and both

The Ugaritic Rapiʾūma texts — same scribal hand as the Aqhat Epic, definitively re-edited in **Wayne Pitard, "A New Edition of the 'Rāpiʾūma' Texts," BASOR 285 (1992): 33–77** — present a feast of divine-and-deceased royal ancestors that maps directly onto the Hebrew Rephaim.

**(a) The texts** [VH on formulae, H on exact line numbers]. **KTU 1.22 I 6–10**: *tlḥm . rpum . tštyn / tlḥmn . ilnym* — "The rpum eat, they drink; the *ilnym* (divine-ones) eat…" **KTU 1.22 I 21–25**: *hlk . ym . w ṯn / aḫr . špšm . b ṯlṯ / mǵy . rpum . l grnt / ilnym . l mṭʿt* — "A day's march and a second; after sunrise on the third the rpum arrived at the threshing-floors, the divine-ones at the plantations." The standing epithet of the host-patriarch is *dnil . mt . rpi / ǵzr . mt . hrnmy* — "Daniʾel, the man of (the) Rapiʾu, the hero, the Harnamite." The parallel pair *ilnym // mtm* — "divinities // dead men" — is the linchpin of the dual reading.

**(b) Who summons** [H–VH]. The summoner in **KTU 1.21 II 1–5** — *iqrakn l bty / aṣḥkm qrb hkly* ("I summon you to my house, I call you within my palace") — is most plausibly **El** (so Pope 1977, de Moor 1976, Caquot 1960), with Daniʾel as living *mt rpi* host-figure. In the parallel funerary text **KTU 1.161** the living **king** (Ammurapi III) presides over invocation of his dead royal predecessors.

**(c) Assembly of Didānu** [VH]. **KTU 1.161 (RS 34.126), lines 1–12** — the *spr dbḥ ẓlm*, "Document of the Sacrifice of the Shades," sole indisputably funerary Ugaritic ritual:

> 1. *spr . dbḥ . ẓlm*
> 2. *qritm . rpi . arṣ*
> 3. *qbitm . **qbṣ . ddn***
> 4. *qra . ulkn . rpu*
> …
> 8. *qrau . **rpim . qdmym***
> 9. *qritm . rpi . arṣ*
> 10. *qbitm . qbṣ . ddn*
> 11. *qra . ʿmṯtmr . mlk*
> 12. *qra . u . nqmd . mlk*

"You have called the rpum of the underworld; you have summoned **the assembly of Didānu**. Call Ulkn the Rapiʾu… call the **ancient rpum** (*rpim qdmym*) … call ʿAmmiṯtamru the king; call also Niqmaddu the king." Didānu/Ditānu is the **eponymous Amorite ancestor** of the Ugaritic, Assyrian, and Babylonian royal lines (cf. the Babylonian kings *Ammi-Ditāna*, *Samsu-Ditāna*; the Sumerian wall **Muriq-Tidnim**; the Assyrian King List's "seventeen kings who lived in tents"). KTU 1.15 III 2–4 blesses Kirta to be "exalted in the *pḫr ddn*." Linguistically plausible but religiously dissimilar link to biblical **Dedan** (Gen 10:7; Jer 49:8) [M]. The Greek **Titanes** etymology (Bachvarova 2016, Annus) is suggestive but unproven [L–M].

**(d) Dead, divine, or both** [VH: both]. **KTU 1.108** opens *hn . yšt . rpu . mlk . ʿlm / w yšt . [il] gṯr . w yqr* — "Behold, Rapiʾu, **the eternal king**, drinks, and El the strong and noble drinks." Critically, **KTU 1.108:2–3 places Rapiʾu at ʿṯtrt (Ashtaroth) and hdrʿy (Edrei)** — the exact two cities of **Og of Bashan** in Deut 1:4 and Josh 12:4. This is the strongest nexus between Ugaritic Rapiʾu-theology and biblical Rephaim. The consensus (Lewis HSM 39, 1989; Pardee 2002; del Olmo Lete 2014²; Hays 2015; Suriano 2018, with Schmidt 1994 a minimalist outlier) is that **the rpum are deified royal ancestors functioning as a lower divine tier**.

**(e) Hebrew dual usage** [VH]. **Living-giants stratum**: Gen 14:5 (Rephaim at Ashteroth-Karnaim = ʿṯtrt of KTU 1.108); Deut 2:11, 2:20 (Emim/Zamzummim "accounted as Rephaim"); Deut 3:11 (Og's iron bed, "remnant of the Rephaim"); Josh 12:4, 13:12, 17:15; Valley of Rephaim (2 Sam 5:18, 22; 23:13). **Shades-of-the-dead stratum**: Isa 14:9 — שְׁאוֹל מִתַּחַת רָגְזָה לְךָ לִקְרַאת בּוֹאֶךָ עוֹרֵר לְךָ רְפָאִים כָּל־עַתּוּדֵי אָרֶץ הֵקִים מִכִּסְאוֹתָם כֹּל מַלְכֵי גוֹיִם — "Sheol stirs the **Rephaim** for you, all the leaders of the earth; it raises from their thrones all the kings of the nations" — the exact Ugaritic council-of-dead-kings scene. Isa 26:14, 26:19; Ps 88:11; Job 26:5 (הָרְפָאִים יְחוֹלָלוּ מִתַּחַת מַיִם — "the Rephaim writhe beneath the waters"); Prov 9:18 (וְלֹא־יָדַע כִּי־רְפָאִים שָׁם בְּעִמְקֵי שְׁאוֹל קְרֻאֶיהָ — note *qruʾēhā* "her called/invited ones," same Semitic root *q-r-ʾ* "to summon" as KTU 1.161's qra-formula); Prov 21:16 (קְהַל רְפָאִים = Ugaritic *qbṣ ddn* / *pḫr ddn*).

**Verdict**: the dual usage is **genuine semantic continuity** preserving an old Northwest-Semitic royal-ancestor cult; the biblical editors **demoted divine status** (Ps 88:11 denies the Rephaim rise to praise YHWH; Isa 26:14 denies they live; Deut historicizes them as merely tall pre-Israelite peoples). The Truth Project's core claim — that the "shades" usage preserves memory of former higher status — is **supported [H]**. The extension to "divine-human hybrid Nephilim lineage" exceeds the Ugaritic and biblical evidence (the Ugaritic rpum are royal-ancestor by deification-at-death, not by divine parentage) and is **L**.

