## Q4 — Exodus 4:24–26: every ancient translator removed YHWH from the attack

The Hebrew text presents YHWH as the direct attacker; every ancient translation tradition substitutes an angelic intermediary. The uniformity of the substitution across geographically and chronologically dispersed traditions is itself diagnostic of acute theological discomfort.

**(a) The Hebrew** [VH]. **Exodus 4:24–26** (BHS): וַיְהִי בַדֶּרֶךְ בַּמָּלוֹן וַיִּפְגְּשֵׁהוּ יְהוָה וַיְבַקֵּשׁ הֲמִיתוֹ׃ וַתִּקַּח צִפֹּרָה צֹר וַתִּכְרֹת אֶת־עָרְלַת בְּנָהּ וַתַּגַּע לְרַגְלָיו וַתֹּאמֶר כִּי חֲתַן־דָּמִים אַתָּה לִי׃ וַיִּרֶף מִמֶּנּוּ אָז אָמְרָה חֲתַן דָּמִים לַמּוּלֹת׃ — "On the way, at the lodging-place, YHWH met him and **sought to kill him** (*wayĕbaqqēš hămîtô*). Zipporah took a flint and cut off the foreskin of her son and touched (it) to his feet, and said: 'For a bridegroom of blood (*ḥătan-dāmîm*) you are to me!' And he let him go. Then she said, 'A bridegroom of blood with reference to circumcisions (*la-mûlōt*).'"

Three irreducible ambiguities: the antecedent of *hămîtô* (Moses or his son?); the antecedent of *raglāyw* ("his feet" — Moses, son, or attacker; with the well-attested *regel*-as-genital euphemism, cf. Isa 7:20, Ruth 3:7); and the plural form *mûlōt* in v. 26b which Childs (OTL *Exodus*, 1974, pp. 95–104) regards as an editorial gloss explaining an already opaque archaic phrase. Propp ("That Bloody Bridegroom," *VT* 43.4 [1993] 495–518; *Exodus 1–18*, AB 2, pp. 218–238) reads the attack as motivated by Moses's **blood-guilt for the Egyptian** (Exod 2:12), connected by the Leitwort *bqš* ("seek the life"). The Arabic cognate *ḫ-t-n* (خَتَنَ "to circumcise," *ḫitān* "circumcision," *ḫatan* "in-law") preserves the dual sense "circumcise/be-related-by-marriage" lost in later Hebrew — the strongest extra-biblical philological evidence that the phrase originally meant something like "one bound by the blood-rite."

**(b) The Targumim — uniform substitution** [VH]. **Targum Onkelos** (Sperber): וַעֲרַע בֵּיהּ **מַלְאֲכָא דַּייָ** וּבְעָא לְמִקְטְלֵיהּ — "the **angel of YHWH** met him and sought to kill him"; Onkelos uncharacteristically rewrites Zipporah's saying as a doctrinally safe atoning declaration: *bi-dmā di-mhûltā hādēn ʾit-yĕhêb ḥatnā lanā* — "by the blood of this circumcision the bridegroom is given (back) to us." **Targum Pseudo-Jonathan** (Maher, *Aramaic Bible* 2, 1994) intensifies: not merely *malʾākhā da-YYY* but **מַלְאָכָא מְחַבְּלָא** *malʾākhā mĕḥablā* ("**destroying angel**") and **מַלְאַךְ מוֹתָא** *malʾakh môtā* ("**angel of death**"); it adds a midrashic backstory — Jethro had prevented Gershom's circumcision — and concludes "*how beloved is the blood of this circumcision that has delivered the bridegroom from the hand of the angel of death.*" **Targum Neofiti** uses Memra language plus *malʾākhā da-YYY*. **Jubilees 48:2** identifies the attacker with **Mastema**; **b. Nedarim 32a** with the destroying angels **Af and Hemah** (Anger and Wrath). The substitution is *uniform across LXX, Onkelos, Pseudo-Jonathan, Neofiti, Jubilees, and the Talmud*.

**(c) Arabic/Islamic — NULL** [VH on the null]. The Qur'an does **not** contain this episode. Q. 28:29 narrates Moses returning from Midian *with his family* directly to the burning bush — no inn, no Zipporah intervention, no circumcision attack. Al-Ṭabarī (*Tafsīr*; *Tārīkh* on Moses), Ibn Kathīr, al-Thaʿlabī (*ʿArāʾis al-majālis*), and al-Kisāʾī all omit the episode. Zipporah is unnamed in the Qur'an. Philo and Josephus also omit it.

**(d) Blood as substitution** [H]. Kosmala (*VT* 12, 1962) and Sasson (*JBL* 85, 1966) read the foreskin as apotropaic *pars pro toto* substitute for the whole life; Robinson (*VT* 36, 1986) reads "feet" as the attacker's feet, with apotropaic marking exactly parallel to the Passover blood on doorposts (Exod 12:7, 22). The narrative position is decisive: Exod 4:22–23 has just declared "Israel is my firstborn… I will kill your firstborn" — and the next verse threatens *Moses's* firstborn. The episode is a proleptic Passover.

**(e) Parallels** [VH]. **Genesis 32:25–33** — Jacob wrestles a *ʾîš* who is later identified as ʾĕlōhîm (32:31 *kî-rāʾîṯî ʾĕlōhîm pānîm ʾel pānîm*), and Hosea 12:5 reinterprets the attacker as *malʾāḵ* — exactly the same Targumic move applied to Exod 4. **Numbers 22:22** has YHWH's anger kindled and the angel of YHWH stationing himself *ba-derek* "on the way" as a śāṭān to Balaam (exact verbal echo of Exod 4:24). **1 Kings 13** has the man of God killed by a lion on the road. Mesopotamian parallels (Lamashtu, Lilītu, *rābiṣum*) supply the demonic-attacker template that YHWH here uniquely occupies in the MT.

**Verdict**: that the MT names YHWH and ancient translators uniformly redirected to an angelic intermediary is **VH-attested editorial discomfort with a vestige of a more dangerous deity-mode**. The Truth Project's "Pretender deity" inference is consistent with the data but not uniquely required — the same data are equally explained by standard rabbinic anti-anthropomorphism and a pre-Yahwistic apotropaic substratum (Childs's view) [M].

