**(d) What they knew or transmitted** [explicit NULL for scripture; M for linguistic transmission]. **NULL**: no named pantheon of ʿAmāliqa idols (unlike ʿĀd whose idols Ṣadāʾ, Ṣamūd, al-Hattār are named). **NULL**: no scripture or *ṣaḥīfa* attributed to ʿAmāliqa. **YES**: linguistic transmission — ʿImlīq as first Arabic speaker after Babel (Ṭabarī, Ibn Saʿd, Ibn al-Athīr), making the ʿAmāliqa carriers of the proto-Arabic linguistic stratum. **YES**: cosmological-gigantological complex via **ʿAwj b. ʿUnuq** — son of a daughter of Adam (or Lamak), 3,000–3,600 years old, survived the Flood (water reaching only his waist), eventually killed by Moses at the ankle. al-Thaʿlabī, al-Ṭabarī, Ibn ʿAbbās (via Wahb): "Jericho was the village of the Jabbārīn; in it were a people of the remnant of ʿĀd called the ʿAmāliqa, and their chief was ʿAwj b. ʿUnuq." **This maps structurally point-for-point onto biblical Og of Bashan as \"last of the Rephaim\" (Deut 3:11)** — one of the clearest cross-confessional preservations of a single archaic tradition (cross-reference Q3). Ibn Kathīr, Suyūṭī, and Ibn al-Qayyim brand ʿAwj traditions as fabricated *isrāʾīliyyāt*, but their presence in Ṭabarī, Thaʿlabī, Baghawī, Khāzin, Qurṭubī, Ibn ʿAsākir is uncontested. **Net for (d)**: the Arabic tradition gives ʿAmāliqa political-genealogical-linguistic depth but almost no theological-scriptural content. They are remembered as builders, rulers, and giants — not as revelation-bearers.

**(e) Blot out the name** [VH text; M for the ontology]. **Exodus 17:14**: כְּתֹב זֹאת זִכָּרוֹן בַּסֵּפֶר וְשִׂים בְּאָזְנֵי יְהוֹשֻׁעַ כִּי־מָחֹה אֶמְחֶה אֶת־**זֵכֶר עֲמָלֵק** מִתַּחַת הַשָּׁמָיִם — "Write this as a *zikkārôn* in the book and set it in the ears of Joshua: for I will utterly blot out (*māḥōh ʾemḥeh* — infinitive-absolute intensive) **the memory/name of Amalek** from under the heavens." **Deuteronomy 25:17–19**: זָכוֹר אֵת אֲשֶׁר־עָשָׂה לְךָ עֲמָלֵק … תִּמְחֶה אֶת־זֵכֶר עֲמָלֵק מִתַּחַת הַשָּׁמָיִם **לֹא תִּשְׁכָּח** — "Remember… blot out the zēker… **do not forget**" — the paradox: remember in order to forget. Rabbinic resolution (Zohar Bəshallaḥ §444): YHWH blots the **upper/Heavenly Amalek**; Israel blots the **lower/earthly**. The Talmudic gloss (Pesiqta de-Rav Kahana, Sanhedrin 96b): "no descendant, no grandchild, no camel of Amalek, no sheep of Amalek shall remain, lest people say 'this tree was Amalek's.'"

The semantics of *zēker* (from z-k-r "remember, mention, name") and the parallel *šēm* (\"name\") are **active vectors** — to "make a name" (ʿāśāh šēm — Babel; 2 Sam 7:9, 8:13) is to constitute enduring being; to "cut off the name" (*hikrît šēm*) is to terminate it. Exod 3:15 explicitly: זֶה־שְּׁמִי לְעֹלָם וְזֶה זִכְרִי לְדֹר דֹּר — YHWH's own self-revelation uses *zēker* as the operative cultic-retrieval term. The parallel ANE practice is well-documented Egyptian *damnatio memoriae* on Hatshepsut, Akhenaten, Ay, Tutankhamun (with explicit theological doctrine of *rn* as one of the five components of personhood that *survives by being spoken*), and Akkadian curse formulae *šumu nasāḫu* "to tear out the name."

The Truth Project's reading — name as cosmic retrieval-key, erasure preventing return/influence — is **VH-rated for Egyptian theology, H-rated for broader ANE, M-rated as the *unstated* ontology beneath the Hebrew command**. The Hebrew text says *what* is to be done; the underlying mechanism is implicit, and the Truth Project's reading is one of two plausible articulations (the other being simpler "forensic memory" + "ethnic extermination," which does not by itself dissolve the *zākôr*/*tiškāḥ*/*timḥeh* paradox).

**(f) The genealogy problem** [VH]. **Gen 36:12**: וְתִמְנַע הָיְתָה פִילֶגֶשׁ לֶאֱלִיפַז בֶּן־עֵשָׂו וַתֵּלֶד לֶאֱלִיפַז אֶת־עֲמָלֵק — Amalek is great-grandson of Isaac. But **Gen 14:7**: וַיַּכּוּ אֶת־כָּל־שְׂדֵה הָעֲמָלֵקִי — Chedorlaomer's coalition strikes "the country of the Amalekite" *generations before Esau*. **Numbers 24:20** in Balaam's mouth: רֵאשִׁית גּוֹיִם עֲמָלֵק — "**First of the nations** is Amalek" — which makes no sense if Amalek is merely Esau's grandson, but is exact if Amalek is the *bāʾida* ʿAmāliqa of deep antiquity. Rashi's *ʿal šēm hē-ʿātîd* harmonization ("named proleptically by future name") is the standard rabbinic resolution; modern critical scholarship treats Gen 14:7 as redactional anachronism; **the Arabic tradition makes Gen 14:7 literal** by deriving ʿAmāliqa from ʿImlīq b. Lāwidh, generations before Abraham. Ibn Khaldūn (*ʿIbar* II) explicitly treats the biblical Eliphaz-Amalek and the bāʾida ʿImlīq-Amalek as two *distinct related* populations — recognizing both genealogies as referring to different groups. John Gill (18th c.) and Easton anticipated this resolution in Western commentary using the Arabic sources.

